<h3>JavaScript Final Project</h3>
<p>For my final project in the JavaScript course, I chose the option to make a calculator. The project came with some files, and it had all of the HTML and things like that already put in, so all I had to do was manipulate the DOM and do the logic.</p>
<p>For the main logic portion, I chose to use a switch statement to determine which button was clicked, and had simple logic for 1-9 to append that character to an array of characters that i used for the display, and when the switch statement detected an operator character, it would save that array to another array of the previous number, track which operator was pressed, and then start appending any new numbers to a newly blank array of characters, so that I could do operations with it.</p>
<p>There was a lot more involved to do things like prevent leading 0s, stopping multiple operators, and stuff like that. If i wanted to continue that, I would modify the logic so that I could do like most calculators do, where when you press 1+1, you can press + again and it calculates 1+1 as 2, then does 2+ whatever next number, and essentially do unlimited operations.</p>
